You shouldn't perform shutdown of the threadpools returned by ThreadPoolManager.
Instead you should create your own ScheduledThreadPoolExecutor instance as follows:




        Suggested change











                    miIoScheduler = ThreadPoolManager.getScheduledPool(getThing().getUID().getAsString());



                    miIoScheduler = new ScheduledThreadPoolExecutor(1,



                            new NamedThreadFactory(getThing().getUID().getAsString(), true));



                    miIoScheduler.setExecuteExistingDelayedTasksAfterShutdownPolicy(false);



                    miIoScheduler.setRemoveOnCancelPolicy(true);






The example above creates a scheduler with only a single thread, but you can increase this number as you see fit.

